/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 84.0 720.0 Tm (byte-identical input produced ten identical verdicts. On byte-identical input at) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 706.0 Tm (temperature 0, the gate model was deterministic in that local test.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 686.0 Tm (Comparing the gate inputs from the original variance-producing runs revealed that the) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 672.0 Tm (only varying field was a wall-clock timestamp recording when upstream data had been) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 658.0 Tm (fetched. The timestamp was provenance metadata, not case evidence. We removed it from) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 644.0 Tm (the gate-visible packet and kept it in downstream records.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 624.0 Tm (After the fix, the same case, run ten times on input that now differed only in) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 610.0 Tm (non-visible fields, produced identical gate inputs by hash and stable verdicts.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 590.0 Tm (This separated input variance from sampling variance. The verdict drift we had) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 576.0 Tm (attributed to model behavior was driven by gate-visible input variance.) Tj
/F2 13 Tf
1 0 0 1 72.0 551.0 Tm (Second Finding) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 72.0 524.0 Tm (Encouraged by the timestamp result, we audited the full gate-visible packet for other) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 510.0 Tm (non-evidence fields. Several fields looked like metadata: navigation URLs, platform) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 496.0 Tm (identifiers, profile fields, runner metadata, and similar fields.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 476.0 Tm (We removed a batch of these fields. On the boundary case, five runs produced five) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 462.0 Tm (identical gate inputs by hash but all returned the opposite verdict from the stable) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 448.0 Tm (pre-cut baseline. The cut had crossed from hygiene into verdict-affecting territory. At) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 434.0 Tm (least one field we had classified as metadata contained information the gate was using) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 420.0 Tm (to reason toward the original verdict. The cut was reverted.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 400.0 Tm (We then tried one field at a time. The next candidate recorded paths an upstream system) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 386.0 Tm (had fetched. It looked harmless. On the boundary case, removing it flipped verdicts five) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 372.0 Tm (out of five. It was reverted.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 352.0 Tm (Two cuts had now failed in the same way: fields that appeared to be metadata by) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 338.0 Tm (inspection affected gate reasoning.) Tj
/F2 13 Tf
1 0 0 1 72.0 313.0 Tm (Canary Discipline) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 72.0 286.0 Tm (After the first over-aggressive cut, we established a protocol for further field) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 272.0 Tm (removal:) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 252.0 Tm (1. Before a cut, run the proposed-removed pipeline five times on one boundary case and) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 238.0 Tm (one clear-direction case.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 224.0 Tm (2. Record gate input hashes and verdicts for all runs.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 210.0 Tm (3. Revert cuts that change verdicts on either canary case, regardless of the) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 196.0 Tm (classification reasoning.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 182.0 Tm (4. Accept cuts that preserve verdicts on both canaries only after a broader rerun) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 168.0 Tm (confirms no wider drift.) Tj
1 0 0 1 72.0 148.0 Tm (The canary discipline caught the second failed cut. Without it, we would have propagated) Tj
1 0 0 1 84.0 134.0 Tm (a verdict-drifting change as infrastructure cleanup.) Tj
/F2 13 Tf
1 0 0 1 72.0 109.0 Tm (What This Means) Tj
ET
